ges onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":45,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret was born about 1410, in Little Bowden, Northamptonshire, England. She married Thomas Allington about 1430, in Little Bowden, Northamptonshire, England. She died on 20 August 1477, in Pytchley, Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 68."},"et":{"about 1410–20 August 1477":"umbes 1410–20. august 1477","1402–1475":"1402–1475","1410–1439":"1410–1439","1438–1491":"1438–1491","1439–1501":"1439–1501","1440–1502":"1440–1502","1410–1477":"1410–1477","1440":"1440","1491":"1491","1502":"1502","about 1439":"umbes 1439","1501":"1501","1402":"1402","about 1437":"umbes 1437","1455":"1455","1477":"1477","1410":"1410","1475":"1475","20 August 1477":"20. august 1477","about 1410":"umbes 1410","Abt. 1440":"umbes 1440","about 1430":"umbes 1430","1439":"1439","1438":"1438","Pytchley, Northamptonshire, England":"Pytchley, Northamptonshire, England","Little Bowden, Northamptonshire, England":"Little Bowden, Northamptonshire, England","Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Clipston, Northamptonshire, England":"Clipston, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1410–20 August 1477":"noin 1410–20. elokuuta 1477","1402–1475":"1402–1475","1410–1439":"1410–1439","1438–1491":"1438–1491","1439–1501":"1439–1501","1440–1502":"1440–1502","1410–1477":"1410–1477","1440":"1440","